dataObjects.subject: http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/SPMInfoItems#Habitat
dataObjects.description:
Habitat Type: Freshwater

Comments: It is found in both permanent lentic and lotic situations such as ditches, marshes and lakes, and is a secondary burrower (Hobbs, 1989). Acosta and Perry (2002) suggest that this species is one of the most ubiquitous inhabitants of the seasonally flooded marl prairies wetlands of the eastern Everglades. Hobbs (1989) indicates that it is tolerant of a wide variety of parameters. Crayfish density was highest in habitats dominated by sawgrass in medium hydroperiod areas and spikerush in longer-hydroperiod habitat of the Evergladesm arl marshes (Acosta and Perry, 2002).

Locally Migrant: No. No populations of this species make annual migrations of over 200 km.

dataObjects.title: NatureServe Conservation Status
dataObjects.description:
Rounded Global Status Rank: G4 - Apparently Secure

Reasons: This species covers a wide range and is a habitat generalist being present in both permanent lentic and lotic habitats and temporarily flooded wetlands. This indicates that P. alleni is tolerant of a wide variety of parameters and reaches maturity quickly providing a fast turn around of individuals. However, disruption of hydropatterns in the Everglades is curbing the species' ability to reach its full reproductive potential with current populations at only a fraction of what they would be if hydropatterns were returned to normal.

Environmental Specificity: Broad. Generalist or community with all key requirements common.

Comments: Hobbs (1989) indicates that it is tolerant of a wide variety of parameters.

dataObjects.subject: http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/SPMInfoItems#Trends
dataObjects.description:
Global Short Term Trend: Decline of 10-30%

Comments: Crayfish density was highest in habitats dominated by sawgrass in medium hydroperiod areas and spikerush in longer-hydroperiod habitat of the Everglades marl marshes (Acosta and Perry, 2002). Disruption of hydropatterns (duration and extend of flooding events) in the Florida Everglades has resulted in longer dry seasons, lower groundwater levels during droughts, and abnormal dry-down rates that directly impact aquatic productivity. Although the Everglades crayfish opportunistically colonized and burrowed in the extensive short-hydroperiod marl marshes, survival and growth in these areas werc significantly lower than in longer hydroperiod marl marsh (Acosta and Perry, 2002). Under the current habitat conditions in the Everglades, the crayfish population size declined over 20 years from saturation density in all available habitats to a stable but low density that was about 13% of the original population size (Acosta and Perry, 2000). Results from a study by Acosta and Perry (2002) indicate that the crayfish population response to the simulated restoration of a 7-month hydropedod would be a rapid increase up to an order of magnitude greater than the current population size.

Global Long Term Trend: Decline of 30-50%
